# cleura_gardener_shoot_kubeconfig (Resource)

Requests a short-lived **admin kubeconfig** for a Gardener shoot cluster on Cleura
Cloud. On create the provider calls the Cleura API to issue a new admin credential
valid for `expiration_seconds`, and stores the resulting kubeconfig in the
(sensitive) `kubeconfig` attribute so it can be passed to the `kubernetes`/`helm`
providers or written out for `kubectl`.

The credential is **short-lived by design**. The provider rotates it by *replacing*
the resource — minting a brand-new kubeconfig — as it approaches expiry (see
[Credential lifecycle and rotation](#credential-lifecycle-and-rotation) below).

Attributes at a glance (the generated table further down lists types but carries no
per-attribute text — the schema has no descriptions yet):

- `shoot_name` *(Required, forces replacement)* — the shoot to issue the kubeconfig
  for. Changing it reissues the credential.
- `expiration_seconds` *(Required, forces replacement)* — requested validity of the
  minted credential, in seconds. Changing it reissues the credential.
- `renew_before_expiry_seconds` *(Optional, default `0`)* — how many seconds *before*
  expiry a Terraform run should proactively rotate the credential. Must stay **below**
  `expiration_seconds` (see the churn warning below).
- `kubeconfig` *(Read-only, sensitive)* — the minted admin kubeconfig. Stored in
  Terraform state; treat state as a secret.
- `last_applied` *(Read-only)* — RFC3339 timestamp of when the current kubeconfig was
  minted. Drives the rotation math; not something you set.

!> **Warning: destroying this resource does NOT revoke the credential.** `terraform
destroy` (or removing the resource) only drops the kubeconfig from Terraform state — it
makes **no** API call to Cleura. Any kubeconfig that was minted stays **valid on the
cluster until its own expiry** elapses. Keep `expiration_seconds` short, and rely on
expiry (not `destroy`) to bound a leaked credential's blast radius.

### Prerequisites

- The provider must be authenticated and scoped to the project that owns the shoot.
  Credentials resolve as **provider config > `CLEURA_*` env > the `cleura` CLI
  (`cleura login`)**; `region` and `project_id` are always taken from the provider
  configuration or environment, never from the CLI. See the provider's
  [Authentication](../index.md#authentication) documentation for the full setup.
- A `cleura_gardener_shoot` (or an existing shoot) whose `name` you pass to
  `shoot_name`.

